38 A BILL
39 TO BE ENTITLED
40 AN ACT
41
42 Relating to wheelchair repair; to amend Section
43 34-14C-6, Code of Alabama 1975, to provide the Board of Home
44 Medical Equipment with authority to discipline licensees who
45 fail to repair customized wheelchairs in a timely manner; to
46 provide standards for timely repair of customized wheelchairs;
47 to require Medicaid to cover the cost of customized
48 wheelchairs when medically necessary; to limit the requirement
49 of prior authorization by Medicaid or private health insurance
50 for repair of certain customized wheelchairs; to impose a
51 reporting requirement on Medicaid repair providers; to require
52 manufacturers to provide the documentation, parts, or tools
53 necessary to repair a motorized wheelchair to independent
54 repair businesses on the same terms as provided to the
55 manufacturer's authorized repair businesses; and to provide
56 that a violation of this requirement is an unlawful trade
Page 2

that a violation of this requirement is an unlawful trade
HB258 INTRODUCED
57 practice under Chapter 19 of Title 8, Code of Alabama 1975.
58 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
59 Section 1. (a) For the purposes of this section, the
60 following terms have the following meanings:
61 (1) CONSUMER. The individual who uses a a customized
62 wheelchair in his or her residence, regardless of whether the
63 purchase or lease of the wheelchair is funded in whole or in
64 part by the consumer or by private or public health insurance.
65 (2) CUSTOMIZED WHEELCHAIR. A manual or motorized
66 wheelchair that is individually configured for the consumer
67 with specialized equipment that requires evaluation,
68 configuration, fitting, adjustment, programming, and long-term
69 maintenance and repair services.
70 (3) REPAIR PROVIDER. An authorized repair provider or
71 an independent repair provider, both as defined in Section 5
72 of this act, that repairs customized wheelchairs and that may
73 or may not be a home medical services provider subject to
74 Chapter 14C of Title 34, Code of Alabama 1975.
75 (b)(1) A repair provider shall make timely repair of a
76 customized wheelchair according to the requirements of this
77 subsection.
78 (2) Upon request, a repair provider shall make timely
79 repair of a customized wheelchair at the consumer's residence
80 if the consumer attests that he or she is unable to have the
81 wheelchair delivered to the repair provider's place of
82 business.
83 (3) A repair provider shall maintain and advertise an
84 electronic mail address and a phone number so that a consumer
Page 3

electronic mail address and a phone number so that a consumer
HB258 INTRODUCED
85 may request a repair.
86 (4)a. A repair provider fails to make timely repair of
87 a customized wheelchair for any of the following reasons:
88 1. Failure to respond to a consumer who requests
89 assessment or repair no later than the end of the first full
90 business day after the consumer makes the request.
91 2. If the wheelchair is delivered to the repair
92 provider's place of business, failure to assess and identify
93 the repairs necessary no later than the end of the first full
94 business day after delivery.
95 3. If the consumer is unable to have the wheelchair
96 delivered to the repair provider's place of business, failure
97 to assess and identify the repairs necessary no later than the
98 end of the third full business day after submission of the
99 request for assessment or repair by the consumer.
100 4. If the repair may be covered by private or public
101 health insurance, failure to submit a request for prior
102 authorization within one business day of identifying the
103 necessary repairs.
104 5. Failure to order the parts required for repair no
105 later than three business days after: (i) assessing the need
106 for repair; and if required, (ii) receiving prior
107 authorization from private or publicly funded health
108 insurance.
109 6. Failure to repair the wheelchair no later than three
110 business days after receiving the parts ordered.
111 b. A repair provider makes timely repair of a
112 customized wheelchair in any of the following circumstances:
Page 4

customized wheelchair in any of the following circumstances:
HB258 INTRODUCED
113 1. The repair provider completes necessary repair of
114 the wheelchair no later than 10 business days after the
115 original request is submitted, even if the repair provided
116 fails to comply with any requirement described in paragraph a.
117 2. The necessary repair is completed more than 10
118 business days after the original request is submitted because:
119 (i) The consumer fails to make the wheelchair available
120 for assessment or repair by missing an agreed upon appointment
121 with the repair provider for an assessment or repair at the
122 consumer's home or the repair provider's place of business; or
123 (ii) Shipment of the parts necessary for repair are
124 ordered but not received, or through no fault of the repair
125 provider, the shipment omits necessary parts or contains the
126 wrong parts; or
127 (iii) Any other reason that is beyond the control of
128 the repair provider, including a delay in receiving prior
129 authorization from private or public health insurance.
130 c. If a consumer is required to use a repair provider
131 that is designated by private or publicly funded insurance,
132 the requirements in paragraphs a. and b. shall become
133 operative when the consumer initiates communication with the
134 repair provider designated by the insurer.
135 (c)(1) On and after October 1, 2026, the Board of Home
136 Medical Equipment shall conspicuously post on its website an
137 electronic mail address and phone number to receive complaints
138 about a repair provider that is also a home medical services
139 provider regarding failure to make timely repair of a
140 customized wheelchair.
